When parsing a Markdown file to extract image file names, the primary challenges could include: 1. Identifying the correct Markdown syntax for images: Markdown typically uses the format `![Alt text](URL)` or `![Alt text](URL "Optional title")` for embedding images. Recognizing and properly parsing this pattern is essential. 2. Handling variations in syntax: Markdown allows some flexibility in how links and images are formatted, which might include reference-style image links or inline links with various spacing and line break patterns. 3. Dealing with different types of image URLs: Images in a Markdown file could be linked using absolute URLs, relative paths, or possibly even data URIs. Extracting just the file names might require additional logic to handle these cases. 4. Filtering out non-image links: In Markdown, regular hyperlinks and image links share similar syntax, so it's important to distinguish between them to avoid false positives. 5. Nested parentheses: Occasionally, URLs may contain parentheses, which can complicate parsing since the end of the URL is typically denoted by a closing parenthesis. 6. Escaped characters: Markdown allows escaping of special characters, like brackets or parentheses, which could affect the extraction process if not handled properly. 7. Inline HTML: Markdown files can also include HTML tags, so it's possible that images are embedded using `` tags instead of Markdown syntax. Given these potential issues, it is important to carefully design the parsing logic to accurately recognize and extract image file names from a Markdown file.
